# Dependencies - can be found in meson.build
sudo apt-get install meson gettext appstream-util itstool libglibmm-2.4-dev libgtkmm-4.0-dev libgtop2-dev librsvg2-dev libsystemd-dev libadwaita-dev libsqlite3-dev

# Meson

## configure creates the build directory
meson setup build

## build - compiles the source
ninja -C build

## install - required to be able to run the application
ninja -C build install

## clean - removes built files to do a clean build
ninja -C build -t clean

## start from scratch
rm -rf build


# Driving the UI from a script (developer builds only)

The Health tab is tedious to test by hand: it depends on real drives, on the
history database having content, and on privilege prompts. `-Ddev_ipc=true`
builds a small control socket so a script can drive the running app instead.

It is NOT implied by -Ddevelopment=true, and it must never be enabled for a
release build: it exposes a socket that can drive the UI. It is locked twice —
the code is only compiled with the meson option, and even then it stays dormant
unless GSM_DEV_IPC=1 is set at run time. A default build contains none of it
(verify with: nm build/src/gnome-system-monitor-rh | grep dev_ipc).

    meson setup build -Ddev_ipc=true
    ninja -C build
    GSM_DEV_IPC=1 ./build/src/gnome-system-monitor-rh &

    tools/gsm-dev-ctl tab                  # list tabs, show current
    tools/gsm-dev-ctl tab health
    tools/gsm-dev-ctl size 1150x1050
    tools/gsm-dev-ctl scroll bottom
    tools/gsm-dev-ctl click 'Unlock Full'  # press a button by visible label
    tools/gsm-dev-ctl toggle 'Track wear'  # flip a switch row by title
    tools/gsm-dev-ctl text                 # dump visible text, to assert on
    tools/gsm-dev-ctl shot /tmp/health.png

`shot` renders the window's own widget tree rather than grabbing the screen, so
it works while the window is unfocused, occluded, or on another workspace — and
it never moves the pointer or steals focus the way synthetic input does.




